<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-02-09T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-02-09T02:00:00-05:00" n="331" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d331">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">493.11/2096: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-02-09T15:00:00+08:00">February 9, 1938—3
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received February 9—2:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>97. Following from Hong Kong.</p>
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                            <p>“February 2, 2 p.m. Numerous refugees desire to make claim for
                                personal losses sustained in China. Please advise as to form in
                                which claim should be made; also whether any fee should be
                                collected.”</p>
                        </quote>
                        <p>In view of lack of any details which might suggest some method of
                            settling these claims informally as is contemplated at Nanking, I see no
                            alternative to the use of the prescribed form of “application for the
                            support of claims against foreign governments” but I would appreciate
                            the Department’s comments.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>